---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="pdit - Interactive Python Editor" description="Interactive Python editor with inline execution results">
  <main>
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>pdit</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Interactive Python editor with inline execution results</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What is pdit?</h2>
    <p>pdit lets you write regular Python files and see execution results inline, like a notebook but without cells. Edit in your browser or your favorite editorâ€”results update in real-time.</p>

    <h3>Quick Start</h3>
    <pre><code>pip install pdit
pdit script.py</code></pre>
    <p>Press Cmd+Enter to execute. See the <a href="/docs/">Manual</a> for more.</p>

    <h2>Features</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Inline results</strong> - Output appears right next to the code that produced it</li>
      <li><strong>DataFrames</strong> - Pandas DataFrames render as clean tables</li>
      <li><strong>Plots</strong> - Matplotlib figures appear inline automatically</li>
      <li><strong>File watching</strong> - Edit in your favorite editor and see updates in real-time</li>
      <li><strong>Export</strong> - Share your work as standalone HTML files</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why pdit?</h2>
    <p>Jupyter notebooks are great for exploration, but they can feel heavy for quick scripts. Traditional REPLs are fast but don't preserve your work. pdit sits in between: you write regular Python files, but see results inline like a notebook.</p>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  h1 {
    font-size: 3rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }
  .hero {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
    border-bottom: 3px solid #1a1a1a;
  }
  .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: #555;
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
</style>
